entry.content:
We did this as part of LayoutNG originally to correctly position OOFs

within split inlines.

As part of the "block-in-inline" project we removed inline-splitting!



As such we can re-allow anonymous blocks to be containing blocks. This

happens when an inline () is a container for an OOF, but we

position it relative to an anonymous wrapping block (created for

block-in-inline purposes for example).

entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2: Finish V4L2StatefulVD H.264 frame slicing/gathering
entry.content:
This CL finishes fixing most of the H.264 frame/fragment situation;

it simplifies H264FrameReassembler::Process() to only support three

clear cases for a NALU processing: it's either

- A whole frame in itself or

- A fragment of a frame or

- A fragment of a frame _and_ it marks the beginning of a new frame

(but it doesn't know whether itself is a new frame or not, we have

to wait for the next NALU parsing).



To clarify a bit these three cases, this CL extends

FindH264FrameBoundary() to return a FrameBoundaryInfo,

hopefully simplifying the information returned.



A side effect of splitting multiple-frames-per-DecoderBuffer is that

some odd case like CAPCM1_Sand_E, which is composed of a giant

DecoderBuffer containing 30 full frames, is now enqueued in 30

OUTPUT buffers, so this CL makes the |OUTPUT_queue_| a bit longer.

This is needed for Hana but not for Trogdor: subsequent CLs will

teach the code not to split multiple-frame-per-DecoderBuffer on

such platform.



With this, Trogdor doesn't regress and Hana is at parity or better

than ToT; failing ones after this CL would be:



baseline: HCBP1_HHI_A.h264 HCBP2_HHI_A.h264 LS_SVA_D.h264 NRF_MW_E.h264

first_mb_in_slice: MR1_BT_A.h264

high: HCAFR2_HHI.h264 HCHP2_HHI_A.h264

main: CVWP2_TOSHIBA_E.h264 CVWP3_TOSHIBA_E.h264 HCMP1_HHI_A.h264



LS_SVA_D is new though, not failing on ToT.

entry.title: [omnibox][actions] Change behavior of matches for keyword mode refresh
entry.content:
This CL does several things to further implement keyword mode refresh:

- Changes click behavior on starter pack matches to select the match

and activate its keyword mode instead of committing the omnibox.

- Prevents the shortcut provider from usurping starter pack matches

coming from the builtin provider. This is necessary to avoid problems

like shortcuts allowing default when the core match didn't, inline

autocomplete changing the result set to skip starter pack, etc.

- Fixes some keyword state handling in the edit model to avoid breaking

existing logic when the feature is enabled. In particular, transitions

from keyword to keyword are now common where they weren't before, and

the existing logic assumes keyword is accepted from normal state.

- Cleans some controls from default match when the input starts

with '@' to avoid interference with the intended user interaction.

This part will be further discussed with the team, but the change

follows the current plan of record so we can try it out (guarded).

entry.title: [Async Clipboard API] Remove unsanitized write permissions.
entry.content:
The definition of sanitization for HTML format write was changed

to write well-formed HTML document instead of a fragment when

`kClipboardWellFormedHtmlSanitizationWrite` flag is enabled.

This was done to address the information loss with the sanitized

fragment.



- The behavior with the flag changed from passing through unaltered

HTML i.e. unsanitized, to passing through well-formed HTML document

that has been processed by the DOM parser.

- The strict `CLIPBOARD_READ_WRITE` permission check was necessary

for writing unsanitized HTML, but is unnecessary for writing

lightly-sanitized HTML.



The `PermissionType` that gates the action of writing HTML format to

the clipboard is being changed from `CLIPBOARD_READ_WRITE`

to `CLIPBOARD_SANITIZED_WRITE`. This has the notable effect of

avoiding a permission prompt in some situations.



The behavior for web custom formats write permission remains

unchanged.

Migrate the SwitchMaterial (GM2) into MaterialSwitch (GM3).



To mitigate the size increase for the MG3 switch, we are applying a 0.8 scale for the switch, while setting a bigger minHeight (60dp) in order to maintain the min touch garget size. This however brings the side effect of size could have a bigger height.

- Migrate the UI using SwitchCompat into MaterialSwitch to keep the consistent look

entry.title: [Hub] Between Pane back press handling
entry.content:
Add a BackPressHandler that tracks focus between panes to maintain a

stack of the most recent visit to each pane excluding the current pane.



On navigation between panes an entry is added to the stack removing

the previous occurrence of a PaneId if one was present.



On back press navigation happens back to the previous Pane in the

stack if it can be focused. If not the process will repeat until

the stack is empty or focused succeeded.

details including what other inputs are required to the

HubCoordinator to make back press decisions for the Hub. In a future

CL, the HubCoordinator will add a handler to BackPressManager to

receive back presses. For legacy back press the back press events

entry.title: Ensure that NativeWidgetMac respects Widget z order level
entry.content:
Currently, on Mac, menus that are created using the |MenuHost| are displayed under floating windows (while also still receiving input events). This is due to the underlying widget having an incorrect z-order.



The issue here is that when Widgets are created we try to determine the |EffectiveZOrderLevel| [1]. However, on Mac (under certain circumstances) we override the Widget z-order [2], which does not take into account the |EffectiveZOrderLevel|.



This change updates NativeWidgetMac to use |EffectiveZOrderLevel| so that the z order level is set appropriately according to the Widget InitParams Type.



Also added a MenuController test to prevent future regressions.



[1]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ui/views/widget/widget.cc;l=170;drc=430c7ea2e0a2e29142869f6efb112a7979ab605a

entry.title: Allow BackgroundDownloaderMac to load content over HTTP
entry.content:
The background CRX downloader on Mac uses NSURLSessions which use App

Transport Security (ATS), requiring by default all HTTP connections be

made over HTTPS. However, it is crucial that this content can be

loaded over HTTP. Among our reasons are that:



1. Proxy caching of updates is critical for some enterprises.



2. The update server expects URLs to be tried in the order they were

sent in the client. Features such as bandwidth shaping may not work

correctly if the client drops URLs from the response set.



To disable ATS restrictions, NSAllowsArbitraryLoads has been set to

true in Info.plist.

entry.title: Avoid dangling pointer to Browser in AutofillContextMenuManager.
entry.content:
The context menu is, ultimately, owned by a WebContents:

- WebContentsImpl owns WebContentsView

- WebContentsView is implemented by WebContentsViewChildFrame, which

owns WebContentsViewDelegate.

- WebContentsViewDelegate is implemented by

ChromeWebContentsViewDelegateViews, which owns

RenderViewContextMenuBase.

- RenderViewContextMenuBase is implemented by RenderViewContextMenu,

which owns AutofillContextMenuManager.



Therefore the lifetime of the AutofillContextMenuManager is tied to that

of a WebContents. However, a WebContents can move from one Browser to

another and, in particular, a WebContents can outlive the Browser that

it started its life in if the Browser is closed after the move.

As a result, the raw pointer that AutofillContextMenuManager keeps to

its initial browser can become dangling.



This CL removes this raw pointer and obtains it dynamically as needed.

entry.title: [Private Network Access] Fix iframe tests
entry.content:
In order to make navigation requests pass the CORS check, we have to

make the following changes.



1. When the request's mode is "navigate", its credentials mode must be

"include" [1], so `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` can't be `*` and

`Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` has to be `true` [2]. We make the

test server respond with these headers.



2. The actual navigation requests will contain

`Upgrade-Insecure-Requests` header, so we add this header to the

`Access-Control-Allow-Headers` that the test server returns.



3. `Accept` header value size of a navigation request can exceed the

safe limit 128, so I relaxed the limit behind a flag.



[1] https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#concept-request-credentials-mode

[2] https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#cors-protocol-and-credentials

entry.content:
the current error, notification, or update state.

entry.title: blink: Oilpanize the InterpolableValue hierarchy
entry.content:
InterpolableValue and friends are one of the most frequently

malloc-allocated objects on Speedometer2/3. Oilpanizing the hierarchy

results in 0.5-0.6% Speedometer2 improvement, likely due to improved

locality and faster allocation.



The CL also avoids finalization for those classes to make sure that

main-thread sweeping doesn't regress.



Design doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1CkqzjCf7hLBCOU8NL2EoMPfeoq6iGmN8ndBm0w7uPpQ/edit?usp=sharing
